   "source": [
    "# 1. Is it possible that an event is independent of itself? If so, when?\n",
    "\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "af6ae27f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Ans :\n",
    "    Yes, It is possible for an event to be independent of itself.\n",
    "    An Event is independent of themselves if they have probability either 0 or 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "Reason:\n",
    "    If P(A)=0 then P(A ∩ B)= 0 and if P(A)= 1 then P(A∩B)= P(B). In either case we have P(A∩B)= P(A)P(B). The independence of A with itself gives P(A) = (P(A))^2 and hence either P(A)= 0 or P(A)= 1 ."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "ac1a8709",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": []
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9f00e6b6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 2. Is it always true that if A and B are independent events, then Ac and Bc are independent events? Show that it is, or give a counterexample."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f6f24d3c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Ans:\n",
    "    Yes, if A and B are independent events then complement of them i.e. Ac and Bc are also independent.\n",
    "    \n",
    "Reason:\n",
    "    P(Ac∩Bc)=1−P(A∪B)\n",
    "        =1−P(A)−P(B)+P(A∩B)\n",
    "        =1−P(A)−P(B)+P(A)P(B)\n",
    "        =(1−P(A))(1−P(B))\n",
    "        =P(Ac)P(Bc)."
   ]
  },
